        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer145524426" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6080421392499295931">My dear friend Bev sent me this book, thank you Bev! I am not a Buddhist, but I didn&apos;t feel that I needed to be in order to grasp the main points and gain insight from all of the lessons within. I think this book is perfect for all who are chronically ill, or care givers of the chronically ill, looking for a guide on how to better navigate and cope with the mental side of being ill. I know for me being chronically ill there is an overwhelming feeling of helplessness knowing you can&apos;t change the </span>
  <span id="freeText6080421392499295931" style="display:none">My dear friend Bev sent me this book, thank you Bev! I am not a Buddhist, but I didn't feel that I needed to be in order to grasp the main points and gain insight from all of the lessons within. I think this book is perfect for all who are chronically ill, or care givers of the chronically ill, looking for a guide on how to better navigate and cope with the mental side of being ill. I know for me being chronically ill there is an overwhelming feeling of helplessness knowing you can't change the physical, but Bernhard shows through a series of simple practices that a change in perspective can lead you right out of that negative space mentally. One of my favorites is this affirmation: There is sickness here, but "I" am not sick. Very empowering! I will refer to this book again and again.</span>
